  <entry>
    <title>Homework #11, due M 11/23</title>
    <author>
      <name>Marco Varisco</name>
      <email>marco@math.binghamton.edu</email>
      <uri>http://www.math.binghamton.edu/marco/</uri>
    </author>
    <id>tag:marco@math.binghamton.edu,2009-11-20:hw11</id>
    <updated>2009-11-20T18:40:00Z</updated>
    <link href="http://www.math.binghamton.edu/marco/topology/#hw11"/>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[
      In parts B] and&nbsp;C] below, the symbol <em>R</em> denotes
      (as usual) the real numbers with the standard topology.<br/>
      A]&nbsp;Suppose that <em>X</em> and&nbsp;<em>Y</em> are
      topological spaces and that
      <em>f</em>:&nbsp;<em>X</em>&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;<em>Y</em> is a
      continuous function. Show that if <em>X</em> is compact then
      <em>f(X)</em> is compact.<br/>
      B]&nbsp;Suppose that <em>C</em> is a non-empty compact subspace
      of&nbsp;<em>R</em>. Show that <em>C</em> has a least element,
      i.e., that there exists <em>c</em>&isin;<em>C</em> such that
      for all&nbsp;<em>x</em>&isin;<em>C</em> we have
      <em>c</em>&le;<em>x</em>. (Hint: argue by contradiction, and
      observe that
      {&nbsp;(<em>x,&infin;</em>)&nbsp;|&nbsp;<em>x</em>&isin;<em>C</em>&nbsp;}
      is an open cover of&nbsp;<em>C</em> if and only if <em>C</em>
      does not have a least element.) Is&nbsp;<em>c</em> unique?<br/>
      C]&nbsp;Suppose that <em>X</em> is a non-empty compact
      topological space and that
      <em>f</em>:&nbsp;<em>X</em>&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;<em>R</em> is a
      continuous function. Use parts A] and&nbsp;B] to show
      that there exists <em>m</em>&isin;<em>X</em> such that
      for all&nbsp;<em>x</em>&isin;<em>X</em> we have
      <em>f(m)</em>&le;<em>f(x)</em>. Is&nbsp;<em>m</em> unique?
    ]]></content>
  </entry>

