  <entry>
    <title>Homework #3, due M 9/21</title>
    <author>
      <name>Marco Varisco</name>
      <email>marco@math.binghamton.edu</email>
      <uri>http://www.math.binghamton.edu/marco/</uri>
    </author>
    <id>tag:marco@math.binghamton.edu,2009-11-10:hw3</id>
    <updated>2009-11-10T23:30:06Z</updated>
    <link href="http://www.math.binghamton.edu/marco/topology/#hw3"/>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[
      A]&nbsp;Let <em>(X,d)</em> be an arbitrary metric space.
      Prove that for all distinct points 
      <em>x<sub>1</sub></em> and&nbsp;<em>x<sub>2</sub></em>
      in&nbsp;<em>X</em> there exist positive real numbers
      <em>&epsilon;<sub>1</sub></em> and&nbsp;<em>&epsilon;<sub>2</sub></em>
      such that
      <em>B<sub>d</sub>(x<sub>1</sub>;&epsilon;<sub>1</sub>)</em> and
      <em>B<sub>d</sub>(x<sub>2</sub>;&epsilon;<sub>2</sub>)</em> are
      disjoint.<br/>
      B]&nbsp;Find a metric space and two balls in it such that the
      ball with smaller radius contains and is not equal to the ball
      with larger radius.
    ]]></content>
